---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import { marsLocations } from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'gale-crater');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Gale Crater location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Gale Crater - Mars Location" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-red-900 to-red-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          Curiosity rover's view of Mount Sharp from Gale Crater floor
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">NASA/JPL-Caltech/MSSS</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Gale Crater stands as one of Mars' most scientifically significant
          locations, serving as the primary exploration site for NASA's
          Curiosity rover since 2012. This 154-kilometer-wide impact crater was
          formed approximately 3.5-3.8 billion years ago and contains compelling
          evidence of Mars' ancient habitability potential.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The crater is dominated by Mount Sharp (Aeolis Mons), a
          5.5-kilometer-tall layered mountain that preserves billions of years
          of Martian geological history. Each layer tells a story of changing
          environmental conditions, from ancient lake beds to desert formations,
          making it a natural archive of Mars' climatic evolution.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Recent discoveries by Curiosity have revolutionized our understanding
          of water's persistence on Mars, with evidence suggesting that water
          activity continued much longer than previously thought, potentially
          extending the window for past habitability.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Facts Sidebar -->
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Quick Facts</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Diameter:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">154 km</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Age:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">3.5-3.8 billion years</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Central Peak:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Mount Sharp (5.5 km high)</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Current Explorer:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Curiosity Rover (2012-present)</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Key Discovery:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Ancient lake environment</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Mount Sharp Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Mount Sharp: A Geological Time Machine
    </h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-8 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Mount Sharp represents one of the most remarkable geological features on
        Mars. This towering mountain wasn't built by volcanic activity, but
        rather by billions of years of sedimentary deposition. The layered
        structure preserves a detailed record of Mars' environmental
        transitions, from wet to dry conditions.
      </p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Lower Layers</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            Rich in clay minerals formed in neutral pH water conditions,
            indicating a potentially habitable ancient environment. These layers
            suggest extensive lake systems existed for extended periods.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Upper Layers</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            Contain sulfate minerals formed in more acidic conditions, marking
            the transition to the drier, more hostile environment we see today.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Recent Discoveries Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Recent Groundbreaking Discoveries
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-yellow-900/50 to-yellow-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-yellow-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Pure Sulfur Crystals (2024)
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          In a stunning discovery, Curiosity accidentally crushed a rock
          revealing yellow sulfur crystals - the first pure elemental sulfur
          found on Mars. This discovery has puzzled scientists as it forms only
          under very specific conditions not previously associated with Gale
          Crater.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The discovery occurred in the Gediz Vallis channel, an area carved by
          ancient floods that left dramatic evidence of Mars' violent water
          activity.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-900/50 to-blue-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-blue-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Boxwork Formations (2024)
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Curiosity has captured unprecedented close-up images of "boxwork"
          patterns - crisscrossing ridges formed by ancient groundwater. These
          formations provide dramatic evidence that water persisted in the
          region much longer than previously thought.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The patterns stretch across miles and were likely formed when
          groundwater left mineral deposits in rock fractures, which then
          hardened and became visible through erosion.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Extended Water Activity Evidence
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Recent analysis of sediment deformation structures suggests that water
        persisted in Gale Crater during Mars' supposed "dry period." This
        finding extends the timeline of potential habitability and challenges
        our understanding of Mars' climate evolution.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        Chemical reactions caused by water have left "halo" shapes in rocks,
        providing clear evidence of water-rock interactions that occurred long
        after the main lake period ended.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Curiosity Mission Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Curiosity's Journey of Discovery
    </h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Since landing on August 5, 2012, NASA's Curiosity rover has
          transformed our understanding of Gale Crater and Mars' potential for
          ancient life. The rover has drilled 41 rock samples, analyzed
          thousands of targets, and traveled over 29 kilometers across the
          crater floor and up Mount Sharp's foothills.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              2012-2014: Initial Discoveries
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Early confirmation of ancient lake environment with neutral pH
              water suitable for life.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-orange-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              2014-2019: Mount Sharp Ascent
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Detailed analysis of the mountain's layers revealing Mars' climate
              transition.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-yellow-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              2020-Present: Revolutionary Discoveries
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Sulfur crystals, boxwork formations, and evidence of extended
              water activity.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Mission Achievements
        </h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Distance Traveled:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">29+ km</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Rock Samples:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">41 drilled</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Sol (Martian days):</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">4,600+</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Images Taken:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">800,000+</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Terraforming Potential Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Terraforming Assessment
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-green-900/30 to-green-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-green-700/50"
    >
      <div class="flex items-center mb-6">
        <div
          class="w-12 h-12 bg-green-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-4"
        >
          <span class="text-white font-bold text-xl">8</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">
            High Terraforming Potential
          </h3>
          <p class="text-green-300">
            Excellent geological diversity and resources
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Advantages</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Proven ancient habitability</li>
            <li>• Diverse mineral resources</li>
            <li>• Evidence of sustained water activity</li>
            <li>• Varied topography with Mount Sharp</li>
            <li>• Rich geological history</li>
            <li>• Accessible location near equator</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Challenges</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Dust accumulation issues</li>
            <li>• Seasonal temperature variations</li>
            <li>• Limited current water access</li>
            <li>• Radiation exposure on crater floor</li>
            <li>• Pervasive Martian dust</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Scientific Significance Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Scientific Significance
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Astrobiology Impact
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Gale Crater has provided the strongest evidence to date that Mars once
          had conditions suitable for life. The discovery of organic compounds,
          seasonal methane variations, and ancient lake environments has made it
          a cornerstone location for astrobiology research.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Climate Evolution Understanding
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The detailed stratigraphic record preserved in Mount Sharp provides
          unprecedented insights into how Mars transitioned from a potentially
          habitable world to its current state, informing models of planetary
          climate evolution.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Future Exploration Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Future Exploration Opportunities
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/30 to-purple-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
    >
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        While Curiosity continues its mission, Gale Crater remains a priority
        target for future Mars exploration. The recent discoveries of sulfur
        crystals and boxwork formations have opened new questions about Mars'
        geological processes and potential for past life.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Proposed Investigations
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Detailed sulfur formation analysis</li>
            <li>• Boxwork pattern comprehensive mapping</li>
            <li>• Mount Sharp summit exploration</li>
            <li>• Advanced organic compound detection</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Sample Return Potential
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Preserved organic-rich samples</li>
            <li>• Diverse mineral assemblages</li>
            <li>• Ancient lake sediments</li>
            <li>• Unique sulfur formations</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- External Resources Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Learn More</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">NASA Resources</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://science.nasa.gov/mission/msl-curiosity/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Mars Science Laboratory Mission
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://mars.nasa.gov/msl/home/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Curiosity Rover Official Site
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/nasas-curiosity-rover-discovers-a-surprise-in-a-martian-rock"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Latest Sulfur Discovery News
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Scientific Papers</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://phys.org/news/2024-03-persisted-mars-gale-crater-longer.html"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Water Persistence Evidence (2024)
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mars-rover-curiosity-images-ridges-planet-water-discovery/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Boxwork Formation Discovery
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</LocationLayout>

